[1]
Date: Mon 27 Sep 2004
From: Nati Elkin <Elkin@poultrymed.com>
Source: The Australian online, Mon 27 Sep 2004 [edited]
<http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5744,10894335%255E1702,00.html>

Thailand: 2nd human case of avian influenza virus confirmed
-----------------------------------------------
A 32-year-old Thai woman was today [Mon 27 Sep 2004] confirmed to be
suffering from bird flu, the 2nd confirmed human case of the disease since
the country's latest outbreak began in July 2004. The woman was confirmed
to have the H5N1 subtype virus, but her condition was improving, Charal
Trinwuthipong, Director-general of the Disease Control Department, said. A
diagnostic test on the woman, conducted on Fri 24 Sep 2004, had turned out
negative. A 2nd test gave a positive result, Charal said. Although she is
believed to have come into contact with chickens, authorities are still
investigating the possibility that she got the disease through
human-to-human transmission. The woman's sister, aged 26, died on 20 Sep
2004 in a hospital near Bangkok. She is not known to have come into contact
with chickens or birds, but she had spent about a week in close contact
with her 11-year-old daughter until the girl's death in a hospital, on 12
Sep 2004, in the northern Kamphaengphet province. The girl also had bird
flu-like symptoms, but no tests could be done on her, because she had
already been cremated by the time officials were alerted.
Health experts are worried about the possibility of the avian virus
combining with a human influenza virus to create a more deadly version that
could easily be spread among people, giving rise to a possible global
pandemic. A bird flu outbreak in Hong Kong in 1997 killed 6 people and
resulted in limited human-to-human transmission. Those who got the disease
from other people experienced only minor symptoms, and there was no
evidence that the virus had mutated into a highly dangerous form.
9 people have died as a result of infection with avian influenza A (H5N1)
virus in Thailand -- including an 18-year-old man last month [August 2004]
-- in the latest round of the disease that began in July 2004. 8 other
people died earlier in the year. The disease also has killed 19 people in
Viet Nam, and tens of millions of chickens, and other birds, have died or
been culled throughout much of Asia.
--
Nati Elkin
<Elkin@poultrymed.com>
